For example,</span></div><div  class = 'S6'><span texencoding="y' = f(t, y), \qquad t \in [t_{\min}, t_{\max}],  \qquad y(t_{\min}) &amp;= y_0." style="vertical-align:-6px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="260.5" height="20" /></span></div><div  class = 'S1'><span>Here a first-order ODE </span><span texencoding="y'=f(t,y)" style="vertical-align:-5px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="72.5" height="19" /></span><span> is defined over the domain </span><span texencoding="t\in [t_{\min}, t_{\max}]" style="vertical-align:-6px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="84" height="20" /></span><span> and the initial solution </span><span texencoding="y(t_{\min})" style="vertical-align:-6px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="42" height="20" /></span><span> is the known value </span><span texencoding="y_0" style="vertical-align:-6px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="14.5" height="20" /></span><span>. </span></div><div  class = 'S1'><span>In most real world practical applications, IVPs cannot be solved using analytical methods so instead we use computational methods called </span><span style=' font-weight: bold;'>ODE solvers</span><span> to approximate the solutions. The simplest ODE solver is the Euler method.</span></div><h3  class = 'S7'><span></span></h3><h3  class = 'S7' id = 'H_ABB5C544' ><span>The Euler method</span></h3><div  class = 'S1'><span>The </span><a href = "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euler_method"><span>Euler method</span></a><span> for solving the first-order Ordinary Differential Equation (ODE) can be derived very easily by truncating the </span><a href = "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taylor_series"><span>Taylor series</span></a><span> after the first-order term</span></div><div  class = 'S6'><span texencoding="y_{n+1} = y_n + hf(t_n, y_n)," style="vertical-align:-6px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="132" height="20" /></span></div><div  class = 'S1'><span>where the subscript notation used is </span><span texencoding="y_{n+1} = y(t + h)" style="vertical-align:-6px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="94.5" height="20" /></span><span>, </span><span texencoding="y_n = y(t_n)" style="vertical-align:-6px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="62" height="20" /></span><span>.</span></div><div  class = 'S1'><span>To apply the Euler method to solve an IVP we loop through the domain and calculate the values of </span><span texencoding="y_{n+1}" style="vertical-align:-6px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="27.5" height="20" /></span><span> using the Euler method with the known values </span><span texencoding="t_{n}" style="vertical-align:-6px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="12" height="20" /></span><span> and </span><span texencoding="y_n" style="vertical-align:-6px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="14.5" height="20" /></span><span>.</span></div><div  class = 'S1'><span>The code below defines a function `euler` that solves an IVP where `tspan` is a two element array containing the lower and upper bounds of the </span><span style="font-family: STIXGeneral, STIXGeneral-webfont, serif; font-style: italic; font-weight: 400; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">t</span><span> domain, </span><span style=' font-family: monospace;'>y0</span><span> is the value of </span><span style="font-family: STIXGeneral, STIXGeneral-webfont, serif; font-style: italic; font-weight: 400; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">y</span><span> at the lower bound and </span><span style=' font-family: monospace;'>h</span><span> is the step length.</span></div><h4  class = 'S3'><span></span></h4><h4  class = 'S3' id = 'H_7CEE008D' ><span>Example 1</span></h4><div  class = 'S1'><span>Calculate the first two steps of the Euler method when used to solve the following IVP</span></div><div  class = 'S6'><span texencoding="y' =\sin2(t)y, \qquad t\in [0,5], \qquad y(0)=1." style="vertical-align:-5px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="263" height="19" /></span></div><div  class = 'S1'><span>using a step length</span><span> </span><span texencoding="h=0.5" style="vertical-align:-5px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="48" height="18" /></span><span>.</span></div><div  class = 'S1'><span>Since we have</span><span> </span><span texencoding="t_0=0" style="vertical-align:-6px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="38.5" height="20" /></span><span> and </span><span texencoding="y_0=1" style="vertical-align:-6px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="41" height="20" /></span><span> then</span></div><div  class = 'S6'><span texencoding="y_1 = y_0 + h\sin^2(t_0)y_0 = 1 + 0.5 \sin^2(0)(1) = 1, \qquad \qquad \quad t_1 = t_0 + h = 0 + 0.5 = 0.5,  \\
y_2 = y_1 + h\sin^2(t_1)y_1 = 1 + 0.5\sin^2(0.5)(1) = 1.1149, \qquad t_2 = t_1 + h = 0.5 + 0.5 = 1.0." style="vertical-align:-18px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="534" height="47" /></span></div><h4  class = 'S3'><span></span></h4><h4  class = 'S3' id = 'H_FAB205CC' ><span>Example 2</span></h4><div  class = 'S1'><span>Calculate the solution of the IVP from </span><a href = "#H_7CEE008D"><span>example 1</span></a><span> over the whole domain </span><span texencoding="t\in[0, 5]" style="vertical-align:-5px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="58" height="19" /></span><span> using the Euler method with a step length of </span><span texencoding="h=0.5" style="vertical-align:-5px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="48" height="18" /></span><span> and compare it to the exact solution given by</span></div><div  class = 'S6'><span texencoding="y=e^{(t - \sin(t)\cos(t))/2}" style="vertical-align:-5px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="114.5" height="19" /></span></div><div  class = 'S1'><span>The function called </span><a href = "#47E46B68"><span>euler</span></a><span> below is defined in the </span><a href = "#H_D56D4A1F"><span>Functions</span></a><span> section at the bottom of this page calculates the solution to an IVP using the Euler method. The input arguments are </span><span style=' font-family: monospace;'>f</span><span> is the name of the funcion the defines the ODE, </span><span style=' font-family: monospace;'>tspan</span><span> is 0);">t</span><span> domain, </span><span style=' font-family: monospace;'>y0</span><span> is the initial value of </span><span style="font-family: STIXGeneral, STIXGeneral-webfont, serif; font-style: italic; font-weight: 400; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">y</span><span> at the lower bound and </span><span style=' font-family: monospace;'>h</span><span> is the step length.</span></div><div class = 'preformatted-matlab' style = 'margin: 10px 3px 10px 55px; padding: 10px 10px 10px 5px; '><div  class = 'S8'><span style="white-space: pre;"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);">function </span><span>[t, y] = euler(f, tspan, y0, h)</span></span></div><div  class = 'S8'></div><div  class = 'S8'><span style="white-space: pre;"><span style="color: rgb(60, 118, 61);">% Calculuates the 'S8'></div><div  class = 'S8'><span style="white-space: pre;"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);">end</span></span></div></div><div  class = 'S1'><span>The program below invokes the Euler method to % Computational Method in Ordinary Differential Equations
% _Dr Jon Shiach, Department of Computing and Mathematics, Manchester Metropolitan 
% University_
%% Initial Value Problems
% 
% Learning outcomes
% On successful completion of this page readers will be able to:
%% 
% * Identity an <internal:H_BD7F876E initial value problem>;
% * Derive the <internal:H_ABB5C544 Euler method> and apply it to solve first-order 
% ordinary differential equations;
% * Express a higher-order ODE as a system of first-order ODEs;
% * Apply an ODE solver to solve a system of ODEs.
%% 
% 
% 
% An <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Initial_value_problem Initial Value Problem> 
% (IVP) is written as an <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ordinary_dif Ordinary 
% Differential Equation> (ODE) where the initial solution at the lower boundary 
% of the domain is known. For example,
% 
% $$y' = f(t, y), \qquad t \in [t_{\min}, t_{\max}],  \qquad y(t_{\min}) &= 
% y_0.$$
% 
% Here a first-order ODE $y'=f(t,y)$ is defined over the domain $t\in [t_{\min}, 
% t_{\max}]$ and the initial solution $y(t_{\min})$ is the known value $y_0$. 
% 
% In most real world practical applications, IVPs cannot be solved using analytical 
% methods so instead we use computational methods called *ODE solvers* to approximate 
% the solutions. The simplest ODE solver is the Euler method.
% 
% The Euler method
% The <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euler_method Euler method> for solving 
% the first-order Ordinary Differential Equation (ODE) can be derived very easily 
% by truncating the <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taylor_series Taylor series> 
% after the first-order term
% 
% $$y_{n+1} = y_n + hf(t_n, y_n),$$
% 
% where the subscript notation used is $y_{n+1} = y(t + h)$, $y_n = y(t_n)$.
% 
% To apply the Euler method to solve an IVP we loop through the domain and calculate 
% the values of $y_{n+1}$ using the Euler method with the known values $t_{n}$ 
% and $y_n$.
% 
% The code below defines a function `euler` that solves an IVP where `tspan` 
% is a two element array containing the lower and upper bounds of the $t$ domain, 
% |y0| is the value of $y$ at the lower bound and |h| is the step length.
% 
% Example 1
% Calculate the first two steps of the Euler method when used to solve the following 
% IVP
% 
% $$y' =\sin2(t)y, \qquad t\in [0,5], \qquad y(0)=1.$$
% 
% using a step length $h=0.5$.
% 
% Since we have $t_0=0$ and $y_0=1$ then
% 
% $$y_1 = y_0 + h\sin^2(t_0)y_0 = 1 + 0.5 \sin^2(0)(1) = 1, \qquad \qquad \quad 
% t_1 = t_0 + h = 0 + 0.5 = 0.5,  \\y_2 = y_1 + h\sin^2(t_1)y_1 = 1 + 0.5\sin^2(0.5)(1) 
% = 1.1149, \qquad t_2 = t_1 + h = 0.5 + 0.5 = 1.0.$$
% 
% Example 2
% Calculate the solution of the IVP from <internal:H_7CEE008D example 1> over 
% the whole domain $t\in[0, 5]$ using the Euler method with a step length of $h=0.5$ 
% and compare it to the exact solution given by
% 
% $$y=e^{(t - \sin(t)\cos(t))/2}$$
% 
% The function called <internal:47E46B68 euler> below is defined in the <internal:H_D56D4A1F 
% Functions> section at the bottom of this page calculates the solution to an 
% IVP using the Euler method. The input arguments are |f| is the name of the funcion 
% the defines the ODE, |tspan| is a two-element array containing the lower and 
% upper bounds of the $t$ domain, |y0| is the initial value of $y$ at the lower 
% bound and |h| is the step length.
%%
% 
%   function [t, y] = euler(f, tspan, y0, h)
%   
%   % Calculuates the solution to an IVP using the Euler method
%   
%   % Initialise output arrays
%   nsteps = floor((tspan(2) - tspan(1)) / h);
%   t = zeros(nsteps, 1);
%   y = zeros(nsteps, 1);
%   t(1) = tspan(1);
%   y(1) = y0;
%   
%   % Solver loop
%   for n = 1 : nsteps
%       y(n + 1) = y(n) + h * f(t(n), y(n));
%       t(n + 1) = t(n) + h;
%   end
%   
%   end
%
%% 
% The program below invokes the Euler method to solve this IVP.

% Define ODE function
f = @(t, y) sin(t)^2 * y;

% Define exact solution
exact = @(t) exp(0.5 * (t - sin(t) .* cos(t)));

% Define IVP parameters
tspan = [ 0, 5 ];
y0 = 1;
h = 0.5;

% Invoke Euler method to solve IVP
[t, y] = euler(f, tspan, y0, h);

% Output solution table
table = sprintf(' t    Euler   Exact \nREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASHREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASHREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASHREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASHREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASHREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASHREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASHREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASHREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASHREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASH\n');
for n = 1 : length(t)
    table = [table , sprintf('%3.2f %7.4f %7.4f\n', t(n), y(n), exact(t(n)))];
end
fprintf(table)
% Plot solutions
t1 = linspace(tspan(1), tspan(2), 100);
plot(t1, exact(t1), 'k-')
hold on
plot(t, y, 'bo-', 'markerfacecolor', 'blue')
hold off

xlabel('$t$', 'fontsize', 16, 'Interpreter', 'latex')
ylabel('$y(t)$', 'FontSize', 16, 'Interpreter', 'latex')
leg = legend('Exact', 'Euler');
set(leg, 'Location', 'Northwest', 'FontSize', 12, 'Interpreter', 'latex')
%% 
% Here we can see that the solution using the Euler method deviates from the 
% exact solution. This is because the Euler method is a first-order method and 
% the truncation errors at each step accumulate as we step through the solution. 
% One way to improve our solution is to use a smaller step length.
% 
% Example 3
% Repeat the solution of the IVP in <internal:H_FAB205CC example 2> using a 
% step length of $h=0.1$ and compare the solution with the exact solution and 
% the one obtained using $h=0.5$.

% Invoke Euler method to solve IVP
[t1, y1] = euler(f, tspan, y0, 0.5);
[t2, y2] = euler(f, tspan, y0, 0.1);

% Output solution table
table = ' t    h=0.5   h=0.1   Exact \nREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASHREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASHREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASHREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASHREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASHREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASHREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASHREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASHREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASHREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASHREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASHREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASHREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASHREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASH\n';
for n = 1 : length(t1)
    table = [table , sprintf('%3.2f %7.4f %7.4f %7.4f\n', ...
        t1(n), y1(n), y2(1 + 5*(n-1)), exact(t1(n)))];
end
fprintf(table)
% Plot solutions
t3 = linspace(tspan(1), tspan(2), 100);
plot(t3, exact(t3), 'k-')
hold on
plot(t, y, 'bo-', 'markerfacecolor', 'b')
plot(t2, y2, 'ro-', 'markerfacecolor', 'r')
hold off

xlabel('$t$', 'fontsize', 16, 'Interpreter', 'latex')
ylabel('$y(t)$', 'FontSize', 16, 'Interpreter', 'latex')
leg = legend('Exact solution', 'Euler method ($h=0.5$)', 'Euler method ($h=0.1$)');
set(leg, 'Location', 'Northwest', 'FontSize', 12, 'Interpreter', 'latex')
%% 
% Here we can see that although using a smaller step length has increased the 
% accuracy of the solution it still doesnt match the exact solution. The Euler 
% method is easy to derive and apply but is not very accurate.
%% 
%% Solving higher-order ordinary differential equations
% The numerical methods that are applied to calculate the solutions to ODEs 
% can only be applied to first-order ODEs. To apply them to higher-order ODEs 
% we first need to rewrite them as a system of first-order ODEs.
% 
% Consider the $N$th-order ODE
% 
% $y^{(N)} = f(t, y, y', y'', \ldots, y^{(N-1)})$.
% 
% If we let $y_1=y$, $y_2=y'$, $y_3=y''$ and so on up to $y_N=y^{(N-1)}$ then 
% we have
% 
% $$y_1' = y_2,\\y_2' = y_3, \\\vdots \\y_N' = f(t, y_1, y_2, y_3, \ldots, y_N).$$ 
% 
% This is a system of $N$ first-order ODEs. We can apply our numerical methods 
% for solving ODEs to each equation in the system to give an equivalent solution 
% to the nth-order ODE.
% 
% 
% Example 4
% Rewrite the following third-order ODE as a system of three first-order ODEs
% 
% $y''' + yy'' - 2y' + ty'' - 10 = 0$.
% 
% Let $y_1=y$, $y_2=y'$, $y_3=y''$ then we can rewrite this ODE using
% 
% $$y_1'=y_2, \\y_2' = y_3, \\y_3' = -y_1y_3 + 2y_2 - ty_1y_2 + 10.$$
%% 
% 
% Solving systems of ordinary differential equations
% Consider a system of $N$ first-order ODEs written in the form
% 
% $$y_1' = f_1(t, y_1), \\y_2' = f_2(t, y_2), \\\vdots \\y_N' = f_N(t, y_N).$$
% 
% Let $\mathbf{y} = \pmatrix{y_1 \cr y_2 \cr \vdots \cr y_N }$ and $F(t, \mathbf{y}) 
% = \pmatrix{ f_1(t, y_1) \cr f_2(t, y_2) \cr \vdots \cr f_N(t,y_N)}$ then we 
% can write the system in vector form
% 
% $\mathbf{y}' = F(t, \mathbf{y})$.
% 
% 
% Example 5
% Calculate two steps of the Euler method used to solve the IVP
% 
% $y'' + y = 0, \qquad t \in [0, 10], \qquad y(0) = 2, \qquad y'(0) = 0$,
% 
% using a step length of $h=0.1$.
% 
% First we need to rewrite the second-order ODE as two first-order ODEs. Let 
% $y_1=y$ and $y_2=y'$ then
% 
% $$y_1'=y_2, \qquad \quad y_1(0)=2, \\ y_2' = -y_1, \qquad \, \,y_2(0)=0,$$
% 
% and we have
% 
% $\mathbf{y} = \pmatrix{ y_1 \cr y_2 }, \qquad F(t, \mathbf{y}) = \pmatrix{ 
% y_2 \cr -y_1}$.
% 
% Calculating the first two steps fo the Euler method:
% 
% $$\mathbf{y}_1 = \mathbf{y}_0 + hF(t_n,\mathbf{y}_0) = \pmatrix{2\cr0}+0.1\pmatrix{0\cr-2}=\pmatrix{2\cr-0.2}, 
% \\\mathbf{y}_2 = \mathbf{y}_1 + hF(t_n,\mathbf{y}_1) = \pmatrix{2\cr -0.2} + 
% 0.1\pmatrix{-0.2 \cr -2} = \pmatrix{1.98 \cr -0.4}.$$
% 
% 
% Example 6
% Calculate the solution of the IVP from example 5 over the whole domain $t\in[0, 
% 10]$ using the Euler method with a step length of $h=0.1$ and compare it to 
% the eact solution given by
% 
% $y = 2\cos(t)$.
% 
% The function called <internal:H_BB766F41 euler2> below is defined at the bottom 
% of this page solves an IVP defined using a system of ODEs. This is very similar 
% to the |euler| function shown earlier with the exeption that the |y| array has 
% $N$columns instead of just 1.
%%
% 
%   function [t, y] = euler2(f, tspan, y0, h)
%   
%   % Calculuates the solution to an IVP expressed using a system of first-order
%   % ODEs using the Euler method
%   
%   % Initialise output arrays
%   nsteps = floor((tspan(2) - tspan(1)) / h);
%   t = zeros(nsteps, 1);
%   y = zeros(nsteps, 2);
%   t(1) = tspan(1);
%   y(1, :) = y0';
%   
%   % Solver loop
%   for n = 1 : nsteps
%       y(n + 1, :) = y(n, :) + h * f(t(n), y(n, :));
%       t(n + 1) = t(n) + h;
%   end
%   
%   end
%
%% 
% 
% 
% The program below invokes the Euler method to solve this IVP.

clear

% Define ODE function
f = @(t, y) [ y(2) , -y(1) ];

% Define exact solution
exact = @(t, y) 2 * cos(t);

% Define IVP parameters
tspan = [ 0, 10 ];
y0 = [ 2 ; 0 ];
h = 0.1;

% Solve IVP using the Euler method
[t, y] = euler2(f, tspan, y0, h);

% Output solution table
table = ['  t     Euler    Exact\nREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASHREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASHREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASHREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASHREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASHREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASHREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASHREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASHREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASHREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASHREPLACE_WITH_DASH_DASH-\n'];
for n = 1 : length(t)
    table = [table , sprintf('%5.2f %8.4f %8.4f\n', t(n), y(n,1), exact(t(n)))];
end
fprintf(table)
% Plot solution
t1 = linspace(tspan(2), tspan(1), 100);
plot(t1, exact(t1), 'k-')
hold on
plot(t, y(:, 1), 'bo-', 'MarkerFaceColor', 'b')
hold off

xlabel('$t$', 'fontsize', 16, 'Interpreter', 'latex')
ylabel('$y(t)$', 'FontSize', 16, 'Interpreter', 'latex')
title("Solutions to the IVP $y'' + y = 0$, $y(0)=2$, $y'(0)=0$", ...
    'FontSize', 16, 'Interpreter', 'latex')
leg = legend('Exact', 'Euler');
set(leg, 'Location', 'Northeast', 'FontSize', 12, 'Interpreter', 'latex')
%% 
% Here we can see that the Euler method solution is deviating away from the 
% exact solution. Once again this is a result of the lower order accuracy of the 
% Euler method.
%% 
%% Summary
%% 
% * An <internal:H_BD7F876E initial value problem> is expressed as an ODE where 
% the solution at the lower bound of the domain is known.
% * The <internal:H_ABB5C544 Euler method> is derived by truncating the Taylor 
% series after the first-order term. It advances the solution over a small step 
% of length $h$ using known values of $t_n$ and $y_n$ to calculate the solution 
% at $y_{n+1}=y(t_n+h)$.
% * The Euler method is only first-order accurate so the solutions tend to be 
% inaccurate unless using a very small value of $h$.
% * <internal:H_46660637 Higher-order ODEs> can be rewritten as systems of first-order 
% ODEs which can be solved using numerical solvers.
%% 
%% Exercises
% 
% 
% 1. Using pen and a calculator and working to 4 decimal places, apply your 
% Runge-Kutta method derived in question 3 to solve the following IVP using a 
% step length of $h=0.4$
% 
% $$y'=ty, \qquad t\in[0,2], \qquad y(0)=1.$$
% 
% 2. Reproduce your solutions to question 1 using a MATLAB program.


%% 
% 3. The exam solution to the IVP in question 1 is $y=e^{t^2/2}$. Produce a 
% plot of the Euler solution from question 2 and the exact solution on the same 
% set of axes.


%% 
%% Functions
% The functions used in this page are defined in this section.
% 
% 
% The Euler method

function [t, y] = euler(f, tspan, y0, h)

% Calculuates the solution to an IVP using the Euler method

% Initialise output arrays
nsteps = floor((tspan(2) - tspan(1)) / h);
t = zeros(nsteps, 1);
y = zeros(nsteps, 1);
t(1) = tspan(1);
y(1) = y0;

% Solver loop
for n = 1 : nsteps
    y(n + 1) = y(n) + h * f(t(n), y(n));
    t(n + 1) = t(n) + h;
end

end
% 
% The Euler method for solving a system of ODEs

function [t, y] = euler2(f, tspan, y0, h)

% Calculuates the solution to an IVP expressed using a system of first-order
% ODEs using the Euler method

% Initialise output arrays
nsteps = floor((tspan(2) - tspan(1)) / h);
t = zeros(nsteps, 1);
y = zeros(nsteps, length(y0));
t(1) = tspan(1);
y(1, :) = y0';

% Solver loop
for n = 1 : nsteps
    y(n + 1, :) = y(n, :) + h * f(t(n), y(n, :));
    t(n + 1) = t(n) + h;
end

end
